429
00:26:36,392 --> 00:26:40,336
Like you said, players say that I took a walk by the lake.

430
00:26:40,336 --> 00:26:43,399
Was that like when you asked the players

431
00:26:43,399 --> 00:26:46,461
or is there also a way for them to self-reflect in the game?

432
00:26:46,461 --> 00:26:47,883
Did you design for that in any way?

433
00:26:48,103 --> 00:26:52,024
We didn't design a way for them to record it within the game, but the game is paced...

434
00:26:52,024 --> 00:26:54,165
Sorry, I'm not repeating the questions.

435
00:26:54,165 --> 00:27:00,908
The question is, are there ways for the players to self-reflect in the game system?

436
00:27:00,908 --> 00:27:02,308
There's two things.

437
00:27:02,308 --> 00:27:02,988
One is...

438
00:27:03,248 --> 00:27:08,790
the journal, which isn't a self-reflection, it's really a collection of everything you've done in the game.

439
00:27:08,790 --> 00:27:14,111
So everything you've looked at and inspected closely will fill your journal in a kind of procedural

440
00:27:14,111 --> 00:27:15,731
list of

441
00:27:15,731 --> 00:27:18,212
like your notes of your experience.

442
00:27:18,212 --> 00:27:25,153
But then we also just designed the game, just quite frankly, to be paced so that there's a lot of time for reflection.

443
00:27:25,594 --> 00:27:27,916
There's even time for reflection when you're doing

444
00:27:27,916 --> 00:27:29,877
your basic survival tasks.

445
00:27:29,877 --> 00:27:32,760
I don't know about you, but when you're doing things

446
00:27:32,760 --> 00:27:35,622
like physical labor, like hammering, right,

447
00:27:35,622 --> 00:27:38,825
or sawing or something, there's actually quite a lot

448
00:27:38,825 --> 00:27:41,927
of time for thinking, and the same with walking.

